04907nam a22007095i 9780674037175DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222002mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740371757 a10.4159/97806740371752doi  a(DE-B1597)574383  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aPQ7081 ǂb F637 2002eb 7aLIT0040502bisacsh04a860.9981 aFranco, Jean, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Decline and Fall of the Lettered City :bLatin America in the Cold War /cJean Franco. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (352 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aConvergences: Inventories of the Present00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tI. Conflicting Universals -- t1. Killing Them Softly: The ColdWar and Culture -- t2. Communist Manifestos -- t3. Liberated Territories -- tII. Peripheral Fantasies -- t4. Antistates -- t5. The Black Angel of Lost Time -- t6. The Magic of Alterity -- tIII. A Cultural Revolution -- t7. Cultural Revolutions: Trouble in the City -- t8. The Seduction of Margins -- t9. Bodies in Distress: Narratives of Globalization -- t10. Obstinate Memory: Tainted History -- t11. Inside the Empire -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe cultural Cold War in Latin America was waged as a war of values--artistic freedom versus communitarianism, Western values versus national cultures, the autonomy of art versus a commitment to liberation struggles--and at a time when the prestige of literature had never been higher. The projects of the historic avant-garde were revitalized by an anti-capitalist ethos and envisaged as the opposite of the republican state. The Decline and Fall of the Lettered City charts the conflicting universals of this period, the clash between avant-garde and political vanguard. This was also a twilight of literature at the threshold of the great cultural revolution of the seventies and eighties, a revolution to which the Cold War indirectly contributed. In the eighties, civil war and military rule, together with the rapid development of mass culture and communication empires, changed the political and cultural map. A long-awaited work by an eminent Latin Americanist widely read throughout the world, this book will prove indispensable to anyone hoping to understand Latin American literature and society. Jean Franco guides the reader across minefields of cultural debate and histories of highly polarized struggle. Focusing on literary texts by García Marquez, Vargas Llosa, Roa Bastos, and Juan Carlos Onetti, conducting us through this contested history with the authority of an eyewitness, Franco gives us an engaging overview as involving as it is moving.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aLatin American literaturexHistory and criticismx20th century. 0aLiterature and societyxLatin America. 0aLittérature et sociétéxAmérique latine. 0aLittérature latino-américainexHistoire et critiquex20e siècle. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / Hispanic American.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)z978311075606708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044220540uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674037175zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674037175423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674037175/original  a978-3-11-044220-5  Harvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-075606-7  HUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)b2013  aEBA_B